metadata.name: Bit: Wise Operator #48
metadata.description:
In full screen view, after animation is ended, click on the graphic to download plottable SVG.

Feature list:
- Color scheme: monochromatic, `cmy(k), my (magenta-yelow), dark-gold, or dark-white
- Fill pens: either Stabilo Point fineliner numbers or UniBall Signo white or gold (but you can use gel pens of your choice!)
- Stroke pen: same as above
- Cell size
- Min. cell padding
- Stroke rotation - true/false
- Fill rotation - true/false

If you have a pen plotter, you can jump straight into making a physical drawing. Please be aware, that physical plot will differ from the digital version due to the pen and paper color differences.

In Inkscape, just align the graphic to A3 size. 

If you don't own a plotter or you want a regular print, simply convert your SVG to raster format.

metadata.name: The Weight of Winter #5
metadata.description:
Description of Seasons of Siskiyou Series

Surrounding my home, covering more than one million acres, is the Rogue River - Siskiyou National Forest which takes up three southern Oregon counties and one northern California county.  It’s a magical place that fills the imagination and lifts the spirit; a place that inspires with its uniqueness, its legends, and its larger-than-life vistas.

Each season in the Siskiyous is a unique experience unto itself.  So, with an attention to the feelings this place evokes at any given time of the year, I designed four generative tokens to create an impression of the emotion–the calming quietness; the peaceful solitude; the overwhelming contrasts and variety of forms, shapes and textures; the magic and playful mystery; the welcomingness and foreboding.  These four works feature clever and inventive creative coding techniques in a rich, graphic style to craft a stunning impression of the Seasons of Siskiyou.


Token 4 of 4 - The Weight of Winter (1990 x 1080) p5js Generative Token.

All good things must come to an end.  After a glorious time of renewal and rebirth, the months of growth and bounty come to a close.  A time of reflection and rest approaches.  All that can be done has been done; and, all one can do is endure the season of slumber.

As light fades with the shyness of the sun, the need to sleep takes over as the creatures of the wilderness test their preparedness.  Travelers to warner lands have offered farewell to those brave enough to stand against the coming snows.  Those who have remained will carry the weight of winter.  The festival of fall had provided so much to carry them through to the colors of spring.  Has it been enough?

The weight of winter can be crushing; but, it’s the pressure that shapes the designs of persistence, endurance and perseverance required to fight against it.  With its paler of indifference, the monochrome landscape of winter hides the brilliance of those schemes aimed at mastering the challenges of survival.  With their perfect adaptations, nature survives to take on winter’s heft with defiant joyfulness and triumphant serenity.  

The Weight of Winter features a generative atmosphere with distant mountains; flow-field conifer trees on noise-wave foothills; a random cluster of subject conifers in the mid-space; and a flow-field tree branch with an interpolated dusting of snow.  Diamond dust – small spears of ice – are simulated with an optical-effect along with random snowflakes.  A generative ‘conspiracy’ of ravens are scattered along the tree tops.

Once the scene is completely generated, a framing box will appear.  Press the DOWN ARROW to save the scene as a png image file.  Click or tap the canvas to toggle full screen mode.

Token Published May 9, 2022 on FXHASH set at 75 Editions.
Written and designed by Ed Cavett using the p5js library.
Token 4 of 4 from the series “The Seasons of Siskiyou.”

metadata.name: Ripple / Cymatic #130
metadata.description:
Mathematical animations inspired by cymatics.  

Symmetric waves ripple around a boundary, causing infinitely complex patterns that evolve forever but never repeat.

Variations are the frequencies and amplitudes of waves, the boundary shape, and the velocity of phase shifts.

Some are contained, others escape to infinity.

metadata.name: Complementary Dot Logic #167
metadata.description:
Complementary Dot Logic was inspired by a series of OP Art paintings done by Victor Vasarely, called Code (Les Bleus). (c. 1967) Vasarely died in 1997 in the early days of computer art. I'm sure he would have embraced this medium. This is the sixth in a series of Vasarely inspired Generative Art pieces I am offering.

I became interested in Victor Vasarely's graphic artworks while I was in art school. As I struggled to learn computer graphics I wondered how do I write a program to produce imagery with a similar aesthetic? I call the process of creating algorithms inspired by other artists: "Art"ificial Intelligence.

My version of the composition has been expanded from the original 3 x 3 to 5 x 5 elements.  However, while there may be a grid of 5 x 5 squares in the composition there is a grid of 9 x 9 circles superimposed over the squares. 

First a random color is chosen for the overall background. Each square is drawn in its place in a random color and that color value is saved. On a second pass the circles are drawn, if they fall in the middle of a square they are rendered in that squares' complementary color. If the circle falls between the squares it is rendered in the background color appearing to alter the shape of the underlying square.

Again, there are many Gestalt interactions within this piece. The most prominent being the figure-ground relationship. The in-between background colored squares form a strong unifying structure, as do the other similar shapes. In Gestalt, similar shapes are seen together as a unifying whole.

Dr. Bill Generative Art OG @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: Coloring With Lines #81
metadata.description:
This project started as a way to teach myself more about classes in p5.js by trying to code the "Chaos Game" method of plotting a Serpinski Triangle

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kbKtFN71Lfs

Once figured out, I expanded the method to other shapes to see if different types of fractals might form. They did not, but the result was a series of points that could be connected with thin lines to draw shapes without using the native functions of p5. After working on colors it seemed like a nice enough project to release for free to everyone. Thank you all for your interest and support, hope you get a cool one!

metadata.name: Whisper #263
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: Deep Seed #100
metadata.description:
"An ancient sketchbook of unknown origin with text that I cant translate.
Filled with many pencil-drawn sketches.
Which in my opinion could be drawings of ancient life forms, probably marine.

Who knows maybe we are looking at the deep seed of art!?"

Hi-res. options:

- press 'i' to save .png with resolution = 1000px x 1000px
- press 't' to save .png with resolution = 2000px x 2000px
- press 's' to save .png with resolution = 6000px x 6000px
- press 'n' to save .png with resolution = 9000px x 9000px

Created using p5js.
